# find-document

Use this when someone asks for a document / file / attachment, or when you
need to find a specific email or file and it isn't obviously in the
engine's recent sync window.

Read-only: this skill **finds and reports**. It never drafts or sends.

## Rule 0 — search broad first (this is where the brain fails)

The most common failure is an over-constrained query that returns nothing,
followed by concluding the thing doesn't exist.

- Start with ONE plain keyword — the term the requester actually used
  ("ricerca e sviluppo", "fattura", "contratto"). Let the store rank.
- Do NOT open with exact-phrase quotes, stacked `subject:` / `from:`
  operators, or `-exclusions`. They destroy recall. Add constraints only to
  trim a too-large result set — never as the first query.
- **A NULL RESULT IS NOT PROOF OF ABSENCE.** Before saying "not found",
  re-run with a broader single keyword and try synonyms.
- If you delegate the search to a subagent, never relay its "couldn't find
  it / it's an attachment" as established fact — re-verify with your own
  broad query.

## Where it lives — look in this order

A "usual" recurring document may be email *body text*, an *attachment*, or
a *Drive file*. Do not assume which; search all three surfaces.

1. **Engine / mrcall-desktop** — the profile's synced mail. Fast, but only
   the recent sync window, and it does not read binary-attachment contents.
   ```bash
   .venv/bin/python -m cs rpc emails.search '{"query":"<keyword>","folder":"all"}'
   .venv/bin/python -m cs rpc emails.list_by_thread '{"thread_id":"<id>"}'
   ```
2. **Google Drive — SCOPED to THIS company's Shared Drive.** Drafts and
   final documents live here. Use the cs service-account, and **scope the
   search to the company's Shared Drive** — never the personal claude.ai
   Drive connector (`mcp__claude_ai_Google_Drive__*`), which spans the
   user's `@gmail.com` and OTHER companies and leaks them into results.
   - `cs drive search "<text>"` — **full-text inside THIS project's Shared
     Drive only** (mrcall-cs → `{{ drive_scope }}`; default scope = config `CS_DRIVE`). It
     NEVER spans other drives unless you pass the explicit override `all`
     (`cs drive search "<text>" all`, test-only). THIS is the scoped search
     — use it instead of crawling folders one `ls` at a time.
   - `cs drive ls [id]` / `cs drive cat <fileId>` — list a folder / read a
     file's text once `search` has located it.
   - `cs drive ls` (no arg) lists the Shared Drives the SA can see — `{{ drive_scope }}`
     for {{ company_name }}, plus any others explicitly shared with it. A different
     company's drive is NOT shared here and must NOT be searched from this project.
3. **Full mailbox beyond the engine's ~60-day window** — `emails.search`
   only indexes the engine's recent sync window (~60 days: `sync.run`
   default `days_back=60`), so a year-old mail is simply NOT in it — a
   null result there is the window, not absence. To reach older mail use
   the claude.ai Gmail MCP (`mcp__claude_ai_Gmail__*`), but **every query
   MUST be scoped to an authorized address**: add `from:` / `to:`
   `{{ founder_sweep_account }}` or `{{ email_address }}`. NEVER run an unscoped
   query — the connector spans the user's personal `@gmail.com` and other
   companies; surfacing those is a privacy breach. No `@gmail.com`, no
   other-company mail, ever.

## Report

Return what you found: the document/text (quote body text verbatim; for an
attachment or Drive file give the filename + location / thread id + how to
open it). If genuinely absent after a broad search across all three
surfaces, say so and list the closest candidates (subjects + dates + ids)
so the operator can decide — do not present a null search as proof the
document doesn't exist.
